[[File:ZenibakoKaisuiyokujo2004-11-29.jpg|right|thumb|220px|The Ishikari Bay in {{ill|Hokkaido|ja|北海道}}, where the legend of Ratoshikamui is told.]] '''Ratoshikamui''' (ラートシカムイ) is a giant {{ill|octopus|ja|蛸}} from {{ill|Ainu folklore|ja|アイヌ民話}}. It is said to reside in the depths of the {{ill|Sea of Japan|ja|日本海}}.{{Sfn|Asari|2021|p=72}}{{Efn|In Ainu, octopus is called "Atoinau."<ref>{{Cite journal|和書|author=奥田統己|title=福島琴蔵（編）『アイヌ語の訳解』|journal=国立歴史民俗博物館研究報告|volume=236|pages=71–86|date=2022-10-31|url=https://rekihaku.repo.nii.ac.jp/records/2000108}}</ref>}} It appears in {{Harvtxt|Sarashina Genzō|1971}}’s {{ill|Collection of Ainu Legends|ja|アイヌ伝説集}}.{{Sfn|Asari|2021|p=72}}
The name "Ratoshikamui" means "God with many tails."{{Sfn|Asari|2021|p=72}} It is considered the strongest god in the sea and is said to have battled {{ill|Furikamui|ja|フリカムイ}}, the strongest god on land.{{Sfn|Asari|2021|p=72}}
== Legend == In Ainu folklore, the Ainu people lived peacefully, avoiding the habitat of the giant bird {{ill|Furikamui|ja|フリカムイ}}.{{Efn|{{Harvtxt|Matsutani|1995}} spells it as "Furikamui," while {{Harvtxt|Asari|2021}} spells it as "Furi."}} However, one day, a woman got lost and polluted Furikamui's watering place, enraging the bird.{{Sfn|Matsutani|1995|p=501}} In its fury, Furikamui flew wildly over the sea and sky, waking Ratoshikamui from its slumber at the bottom of the sea.{{Sfn|Matsutani|1995|p=501}} Angered by the commotion, Ratoshikamui rose to the surface and fought Furikamui.{{Sfn|Matsutani|1995|p=502}}
The battle was fierce, with Furikamui trying to drag Ratoshikamui onto land by grabbing its arms with its beak, while Ratoshikamui sprayed ink and used its eight [[:en:Cephalopod_limb|arms]] to pull Furikamui into the sea.{{Sfn|Asari|2021|p=72}}{{Sfn|Matsutani|1995|p=502}} Their strengths were evenly matched, and neither could claim victory.{{Sfn|Matsutani|1995|p=502}}
When Furikamui was pulled into the sea, it resisted by moving its tail feathers (Ainu: "ishi") from side to side ("kari"), which is said to have given the name {{ill|Ishikari|ja|石狩}} to the nearby waters.{{Sfn|Matsutani|1995|p=502}}{{Sfn|Asari|2021|p=72}}
