In Ainu folklore, the Ainu people lived peacefully, avoiding the habitat of the giant bird {{ill|Furikamui|ja|フリカムイ|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.{{Efn|{{Harvtxt|Matsutani|1995}} spells it as "Furikamui," while {{Harvtxt|Asari|2021}} spells it as "Furi."}} However, one day, a woman got lost and polluted Furikamui's watering place, enraging the bird.{{Sfn|Matsutani|1995|p=501}} In its fury, Furikamui flew wildly over the sea and sky, waking Ratoshikamui from its slumber at the bottom of the sea.{{Sfn|Matsutani|1995|p=501}} Angered by the commotion, Ratoshikamui rose to the surface and fought Furikamui.{{Sfn|Matsutani|1995|p=502}}

The battle was fierce, with Furikamui trying to drag Ratoshikamui onto land by grabbing its arms with its beak, while Ratoshikamui sprayed ink and used its eight [[:en:Cephalopod_limb|arms]] to pull Furikamui into the sea.{{Sfn|Asari|2021|p=72}}{{Sfn|Matsutani|1995|p=502}} Their strengths were evenly matched, and neither could claim victory.{{Sfn|Matsutani|1995|p=502}}

When Furikamui was pulled into the sea, it resisted by moving its tail feathers (Ainu: "ishi") from side to side ("kari"), which is said to have given the name {{ill|Ishikari|ja|石狩|qq=draft|qq=draft}} to the nearby waters.{{Sfn|Matsutani|1995|p=502}}{{Sfn|Asari|2021|p=72}}

